    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-12-31T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-12-31T03:00:00-05:00" n="781"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d781">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002/1073: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-12-31T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 31, 1940—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 11 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1452. Reference Shanghai’s 1081, October 14, 2 p.m.<note n="58" xml:id="d781fn58"
                        >Not printed.</note> Chinese Maritime Customs. Following is summary of a
                    letter dated December 30 received from Inspector General of Customs: Nanking
                    regime is striving to secure similar control of surplus customs revenue in
                    occupied China, but Inspector General has declined to accede to demands made in
                    this connection. He has also declined to acknowledge official communications
                    from the regime, although he has expressed willingness to make informal
                    acknowledgment, when necessary, in English. Inspector General pointed out,
                    however, that he cannot be expected to continue functioning here unless he is
                    permitted to establish informal contact with the <hi rend="italic">de facto</hi>
                    authorities regarding customs affairs. He added that the alternative would be
                    for him to withdraw to free China <pb facs="0735" n="727" xml:id="pg_727"/>
                    which would almost certainly result in disruption of the service and assumption
                    of direct control over the customs by Nanking.</p>
                <p>Sent to Department, repeated to Chungking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
